## 2. Societal and Gender Role Transformations

### 2.1 Impact on Women’s Workforce Participation

The Spanish flu disproportionately affected young men, compounded by World War I casualties, resulting in a labor shortage. This shortage opened unprecedented employment opportunities for women, who entered industries and roles previously dominated by men, including manufacturing, agriculture, and public services. By 1920, women constituted 21% of the U.S. workforce, a 25% increase from pre-pandemic levels ([Blackburn, Parker, & Wendelbo, 2018](https://theconversation.com/how-the-1918-flu-pandemic-helped-advance-womens-rights-91124)).

| Aspect                      | Pre-Pandemic (1917) | Post-Pandemic (1920) | Percentage Increase |
|-----------------------------|---------------------|----------------------|---------------------|
| Women in Workforce (U.S.)    | ~16.8%              | 21%                  | +25%                |
| Women in Manufacturing       | Limited             | Significant          | Substantial         |
| Women in Leadership Roles    | Rare                | Increasing           | Notable             |

### 2.2 Social and Political Empowerment

Women's increased economic participation translated into greater social independence and political influence. The 19th Amendment granting women suffrage in the U.S. was ratified in 1920, shortly after the pandemic. Organizations like the National Federation of Business and Professional Women’s Clubs were founded to advocate for workplace equality and legal rights ([Blackburn et al., 2018](https://theconversation.com/how-the-1918-flu-pandemic-helped-advance-womens-rights-91124)).

### 2.3 Long-Term Gender Dynamics

Despite wartime gains, many women faced pressure to relinquish jobs to returning soldiers post-war. However, the pandemic accelerated shifts in societal perceptions of women's roles, laying foundations for future gender equality movements. The war and pandemic combined to challenge traditional gender norms more profoundly than either event alone ([Wilde, 2019](https://www.bbc.co.uk/bitesize/guides/zx6w2hv/revision/1)).

